#synthesis(title: [The Vagal Structural–Functional Axis in Post-Viral Illness])[
The environments in this cycle assemble a two-route model of how the vagal brake on inflammation fails in post-viral illness, and how confidently that model transfers to ME/CFS. Three convergent themes emerge. First, *autonomic dysfunction has a structural substrate, not only a functional one*: Acanfora's in vivo demonstration of selective cholinergic (VIP+) gastric-mucosal denervation correlating with vagal HRV (@ach:vagal-structural-denervation) sits alongside vagus-nerve viral inflammation and ultrasound thickening, converging with the long-standing cholinergic-anti-inflammatory-pathway biology to give a coherent structural→CAP-disengagement→inflammation chain (@hyp:structural-vagal-denervation-cap). Second, *this structural route is complementary to — not competitive with — the functional autoantibody route* (@spec:cap-autoantibody-blockade): the same endpoint (a disengaged vagal anti-inflammatory reflex) can be reached by destroying fibers or by blocking signaling, and the two-hit prediction is that patients with both are worst affected. Third, *the model is formalizable* as a distinct structural-capacity variable that would impose a ceiling on vagus-stimulation efficacy (@spec:vstr-dag-node). Against these constructive themes, the evidence imposes hard constraints: every direct structural finding is Long-COVID-specific with no ME/CFS gastric histology yet obtained, ME/CFS instead shows *somatic* small fiber neuropathy while Long COVID showed *selectively visceral* loss (@oq:sfn-visceral-vs-somatic), and the founding study cannot even distinguish vagal from enteric fibers, is uncontrolled for deconditioning, and rests on twelve patients (@lim:vagal-enteric-deconditioning). The central open question is therefore not whether the vagal anti-inflammatory reflex matters in post-viral illness — the CAP biology is well established (predominantly in animal models; its clinical significance in ME/CFS awaits direct confirmation) — but whether ME/CFS specifically involves *structural* vagal fiber loss, which a single paired gastric-and-skin-biopsy study in ME/CFS could largely resolve.

*Consequence:* Taken together, these findings raise the possibility that some autonomic problems in post-viral illness reflect physically damaged vagal nerves rather than merely mis-tuned signaling — which would matter for how early treatment must begin and whether nerve-stimulation therapies can work at all — but because the direct evidence is entirely from Long COVID and rests on one small study, the honest current status is a well-motivated hypothesis awaiting a decisive ME/CFS biopsy study, not an established mechanism.
] <syn:vagal-structural-functional-axis>
